div.div:
Refactor job queue system and add enhanced queue API
Replaces the legacy job queue implementation with a modular, service-based queue API. Adds new queue management, monitoring, and auto-translation features, updates Prisma schema for new job and metadata fields, and introduces new service and helper modules for queue operations, chapter detection, file processing, and translation. Updates all relevant routes and entrypoints to use the new queue API.

Refactor job queue system and add enhanced queue API
Replaces the legacy job queue implementation with a modular, service-based queue API. Adds new queue management, monitoring, and auto-translation features, updates Prisma schema for new job and metadata fields, and introduces new service and helper modules for queue operations, chapter detection, file processing, and translation. Updates all relevant routes and entrypoints to use the new queue API.

Add local file storage support and improve export flow
Refactored storage handling to support both AWS S3 and local file storage in job processing and export logic. Enhanced export route to queue jobs and return real export records. Improved project deletion to cancel active translation jobs. Updated upload route to lock project status during upload and handle partial upload failures more robustly.

Add local file storage fallback for uploads
Refactored upload route to support local file storage when AWS S3 is not configured, improving development experience. File upload, deletion, and verification logic now handle both S3 and local storage. Updated .gitignore to exclude uploaded files from version control.

Enhance backend with robust Socket.IO, CORS, and job queue integration
This update refactors the backend server to provide advanced Socket.IO real-time features, improved CORS and security middleware, and more granular rate limiting. Job queue modules are now tightly integrated with Socket.IO for real-time job status updates, and new helper functions are added for queue management, job creation, and health checks. User authentication middleware is enhanced to robustly sync user data from Clerk and handle edge cases. These changes improve reliability, observability, and developer experience for real-time and background processing.
